  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and organizations that work to combat money laundering, including:\n\n1. Financial Action Task Force (FATF)\n- An intergovernmental organization that sets global standards\n- Develops recommendations for preventing money laundering\n- Monitors countries' compliance with anti-money laundering standards\n\n2. United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Provides framework for international cooperation\n- Encourages countries to criminalize money laundering\n\n3. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision\n- Provides guidelines for banks to prevent money laundering\n\n4. International Monetary Fund (IMF)\n- Helps countries develop anti-money laundering frameworks\n\n5. Individual Country Laws\n- Most countries have specific anti-money laundering (AML) legislation\n- Examples include the Bank Secrecy Act in the U.S. and the Proceeds of Crime Act in the UK\n\n6. International Monetary Control Regulations\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Mandate customer identification procedures\n- Implement screening processes to detect potential money laundering activities\n\nThese laws and organizations work together to create a comprehensive global approach to preventing money laundering and financial crimes.",
